er of terms. Thus, (80 + 63 + 100)/3 =3D 81.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><s=
trong>Step 2:&nbsp;</strong></b><span>Subtract the mean from all observatio=
ns. (80 - 81), (63 - 81), (100 - 81).</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>S=
tep 3:&nbsp;</strong></b><span>Take the squares of the differences obtained=
 above and then add them up. Thus, (80 - 81)</span><sup><span>2</span></sup=
><span> + (63 - 81)</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + (100 - 81)</spa=
n><sup><span>2</span></sup><span>.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Step=
 4:&nbsp;</strong></b><span>Find the variance of X by dividing the value ob=
tained in Step 3 by 1 less than the total number of observations. var(X) =
=3D [(80 - 81)</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><span> + (63 - 81)</span><sup=
><span>2</span></sup><span> + (100 - 81)</span><sup><span>2</span></sup><sp=
an>] / (3 - 1) =3D 343.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Step 5:&nbsp;</=
strong></b><span>Similarly, repeat steps 1 to 4 to calculate the variance o=
f Y. Var(Y) =3D 633.333</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><strong>Step 6:&nbsp;</=
strong></b><span>Choose a pair of variables.</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><s=
trong>Step 7:&nbsp;</strong></b><span>Subtract the mean of the first variab=
